Root cause behind OSG returning 500 Internal Service Error - OSG uses aws java sdk to interact with S3 backends. getObject() of aws sdk returns a null reference if the S3 backend responds with 412 or 304 response. 

https://github.com/aws/aws-sdk-java/blob/1.7.1/src/main/java/com/amazonaws/services/s3/AmazonS3Client.java#L1145

{noformat}
            /*
             * If the request failed because one of the specified constraints
             * was not met (ex: matching ETag, modified since date, etc.), then
             * return null, so that users don't have to wrap their code in
             * try/catch blocks and check for this status code if they want to
             * use constraints.
             */
            if (ase.getStatusCode() == 412 || ase.getStatusCode() == 304) {
                fireProgressEvent(progressListenerCallbackExecutor, ProgressEvent.CANCELED_EVENT_CODE);
                return null;
            }
{noformat}

An NPE is triggered when OSG tries to dereference the null object. OSG should definitely check for the null dereferencing. In the current state of the aws sdk, it might not be possible to pass the S3 error (412 and 304 specifically) from the backend due to the sdk swallowing the actual error. 

[~zhill] - may be we should look at processing the preconditions within the OSG scope rather than forward them to the backend. OSG has all the necessary metadata and does something similar with byte range computation since aws sdk does not handle all variants of it. This might also make OSG behave consistently across all S3 backends that may or may not be fully compatible with S3 API.
